CORONAVIRUS DISEASE 2019 UPDATE (439): ANIMAL, DENMARK, MINK, SPREAD, CONTROL
*****************************************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
http://www.promedmail.org
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
http://www.isid.org

Date: Tue 13 Oct 2020 10:29 AEDT
Source: 9News [edited]
https://www.9news.com.au/world/denmark-starts-culling-25-million-minks-after-coronavirus-hits-farms/dac49673-0560-4e6d-b804-9ac8f66e2b4e


Veterinarians and farmers have begun culling at least 2.5 million minks in northern Denmark, after coronavirus was reported in at least 63 farms [see comment for updated numbers].

The Danish Veterinary and Food Administration [DVFA] is handling the culling of the infected animals while breeders who have non-infected animals on a farm within 8 km (about 5 mi) of an infected farm must put them to sleep themselves, Flemming Kure Marker of the government agency said.

"We are moving forward, we are getting it done," he said of the culling that started Thursday [8 Oct 2020] in the village of Gjoel, west of Aalborg, adding it could last months, depending on the spread of the virus. There were no immediate figures on how many animals have already been killed.

On Friday [9 Oct 2020], a mink farmer refused to let authorities enter his farm to cull the animals and a padlock had to be cut, police spokesman Henrik Skals told The Associated Press. Over the weekend, a handful of protesters were removed outside 2 mink farms, he added.

The administration said breeders with non-infected minks will get 100% compensation while those with infected animals will receive less as an incentive for farmers to keep the infection out of their herds.

Denmark is among the largest mink exporters in the world and produces an estimate 17 million furs per year. Kopenhagen Fur, a cooperative of 1500 Danish breeders, accounts for 40% of the global mink production. Most of its exports go to China and Hong Kong.

The coronavirus pandemic could "threaten the entire profession," Tage Pedersen, chairman of the Danish Fur Breeders Association, said. "All breeders are right now in a huge amount of uncertainty and frustration over this 'meteor' that has fallen on our heads."

Scientists are still digging into how the minks got infected and if they can spread it to people. Some may have gotten the virus from infected workers. Dutch authorities say some farm workers later caught the virus back from the minks.

In August [2020], the Netherlands brought forward the mandatory end of mink farming by 3 years to 2021 amid a growing number of coronavirus infections at fur farms. In Poland, another large mink fur exporter, the ruling right-wing coalition and the opposition are deeply divided over a new law that would ban fur farms. Opponents say the law will destroy the livelihoods of hundreds of fur farmers.

